Alcoholics. What made you stop drinking? When I was 16, my whole family died in a car accident. I was the only one who made it. One second, we were driving home from my sister's soccer game, laughing at something dumb. The next, I woke up in a hospital bed with a doctor standing over me, looking like he didn't want to be the one to say it. After that, I shut down. I had no close family, so they put me in foster care. The people who took me in barely acknowledged me. They made me sleep in the shed when I pissed them off. Some nights I went to bed hungry. I started sneaking out, getting strangers to buy me whatever cheap liquor I could get my hands on. By 18, I was homeless. My routine was simple. Wake up, go to work, buy booze, pass out, eat. I had no reason to stop. I didn't care if I woke up the next morning or not. Then one night, I was drinking outside a gas station when a cop pulled up. I kept my head down, waiting for him to tell me to move or arrest me. Instead, he leaned against his car and said, you even old enough for that? I shrugged. Yeah, basically. He looked at me for a second, then nodded toward his car. Get in. I figured, what the hell? Maybe a night in a cell would be better than this. But he didn't Take me to the station. He went inside the gas station and returned with a coffee and a bag of food. He handed them to me and said, eat. I stared at the bag. It had been a while since someone told me to eat like they actually cared. I didn't say much, but he got me to talk. I told him I had no one, no home, nothing. Listened, then told me to wait at the station until his shift ended. That night, he brought me to his place. Couch is yours, he said, tossing me a blanket. We'll figure things out in the morning. I don't know why, but I told him everything. My family, the drinking, the foster home. He just nodded like none of it surprised him. Then he told me he lost his wife in a car accident, too. Said he got it. He didn't try to fix me. He didn't lecture me. He just helped. Took me to get a new I D. Since mine was long gone. Helped me get a better job. Kept his fridge stocked and told me to eat whatever I wanted. If I disappeared for days on a Bender, he didn't yell. He just said, you done? When I stumbled back through the door one time, he found me passed out in my car and didn't say a word. Just opened the door, pulled me up and walked me inside. Sat me down at the kitchen table and put A plate of food in front of me. I could barely keep my eyes open. But I remember him saying, you keep doing this, you're gonna end up like the guys I scrape off the sidewalk at 3:00am. Laughed. Maybe that's the plan. He didn't laugh. Just shook his head and said, nah, not you. I didn't believe him, but something about the way he said it stuck with me. One day he came home and said, listen, I can get you into a program. Law enforcement. You just gotta sober up first. I wanted to say yes. I wanted to believe I could do it. But I couldn't. I told him no. Then one night, he didn't come home. The next morning, I saw the headline. Cop was shot in the line of duty. My stomach dropped. I ran to the hospital and pushed past the nurses until I found his room. He was unconscious, hooked up to machines. They said he'd live, but he'd need help. I told them I'd do it. For weeks.

Always dump lemon on all of my food. I grew up in this crazy household where literally any food was up for grabs. Like, you could make dinner, put leftovers in the fridge with your name on it, and wake up the next morning to find someone already ate half of it. My three brothers and my sister acted like our kitchen was some kind of free for all buffet. I'd buy groceries with my part time job money, make myself lunch for school, and come back to find it gone. Every single time. So I got creative. I started drowning everything I made in lemon juice. And I mean drowning it. Like, I'd squeeze an entire lemon on my pasta, my rice, my sandwiches, everything. At first it was gross, but honestly, I got used to it pretty quick. Actually started liking the taste. The best part? Nobody touched my food anymore. They'd open containers, see my lemon soaked leftovers, and immediately close them back up. Finally, my food was safe. Kept doing this even after I moved out for college and got my own apartment. Just became this weird habit, you know? Like some people put hot sauce on everything, I put lemon on everything. My roommates thought it was gross, but whatever, it was my food. Fast forward to last month. I went on this girl's trip to Miami with five of my friends from college. Split the Airbnb and activities evenly, but everyone paid for their Own food. Since Beth has celiac disease and Jenna's vegetarian and all that, we've been going out to dinner every night to these nice restaurants. I always ask the server for extra lemons. Usually got, like, four or five wedges. And squeeze them all over my food before eating. My friends were used to it by then. They'd roll their eyes and make jokes about how I was probably getting scurvy in reverse or something, but nobody really cared. On the third morning, we're all sitting around the kitchen island eating breakfast, when Beth suddenly goes, okay, I have to say something. You're making food completely inedible for other people. I was confused as hell. I looked around at everyone's plates. Nobody was eating my food. We all had our own separate breakfasts. I was like, what are you talking about? I'm only putting lemon on my own food. She crossed her arms and got this attitude, well, some of us stay up late and want snacks, and your leftovers are the only option sometimes. That's when it clicked. This whole time, Beth had been eating everyone's restaurant leftovers. After we all went to bed. Like, we'd come back from dinner, put our containers in the fridge. She'd apparently go through them later, like it was her personal midnight buffet. I started laughing because it was so ridiculous. Beth, you're mad at me because you can't steal my leftovers. He got super defensive. I'm not stealing anything. It's just how The rest of us feel about food sharing. I looked around the table. The rest of us. None of my other friends said anything. They just stared down at their plates, looking uncomfortable. Beth kept going, we're all friends here. Food should be communal. You're being selfish. I was getting pretty annoyed at this point. If you want my leftovers, just ask. But don't get mad at me for protecting my food in a way that literally doesn't affect anyone else. The breakfast table went.

My husband divorced me to marry my sister and four years later he looked at the child standing behind me and was suddenly shocked. The child was a mini version of him, but called his arch enemy dad. My sister had just returned to the country when my husband handed me a divorce agreement saying our marriage was over. My heart felt like it was being torn apart, but I signed it through the pain. Then, carrying his child, I married his arch enemy. Four years later, he looked at the kid, a mini version of himself, calling his rival dad. His eyes turned red. The pregnancy test showed two lines. Before I could be happy, David threw a piece of paper in my face. Cherry, let's get a divorce. Sign this agreement and I'll give you an extra 20 million. I looked at the well dressed, cold faced man in front of me and couldn't nod. David was getting impatient. When we got married, we signed a contract. Our marriage term is three years. It ends in one month. If you don't agree now, the contract will end automatically in a month. But then you won't get a dime of the extra 20 million. I took a deep breath. David, what if I told you I was pregnant? I admit I was desperate. Even at this point I was trying to use the child to keep David. David's family didn't have many heirs, so for the kid's sake, maybe he'd give Up the divorce. But David's next words chilled me. I had a vasectomy. The kid can't be mine. My mouth opened, but no sound came out. David was my only man. If it wasn't his, whose was it? When someone doesn't believe you, any explanation is useless. David left. I stared blankly at the divorce agreement. My marriage to David was messy. Three years ago, the one supposed to marry David was my sister. But she left the country close to the wedding to chase true love. To keep the cooperation between our families, my family had me marrying her place. David's family agreed for the sake of face. I had a crush on David for seven years, so I didn't refuse. The only unwilling person was David. I didn't know what other people's wedding nights were like. On mine, David tossed me a contract. The same three year marriage contract. After three years, no matter my wishes, the marriage would end automatically. I felt lost and pained at the time. But I didn't give up. I thought if I treated David well, he'd warm up to me. My sister was abroad and I was by his side. One day, he'd seen my worth. For three years, I cared for him meticulously. He had stomach issues. I studied recipes. He had headaches and trouble sleeping. I Learned acupuncture. In hindsight, I was too naive. Who would fall for a nanny? Forget it. We were just torturing each other. I trembled. Trying to sign the divorce papers. Suddenly my phone rang. It was my mom. Cherry, your sister is back. She's on the afternoon flight tonight. Come home with David for a family dinner. My mom sounded unusually happy. I spoke my voice hoarse. Why did she come back suddenly

Nurses, have you ever lied to save a patient from getting in trouble? I was an ER nurse on a military base. There was an accident during training. Accidents happen all day every day, but this one was a flight incident. Flight incidents are a big deal. People die and multi million dollar aircrafts are destroyed. This accident was no different. My patient was the pilot who ejected and survived. Unfortunately, everyone else on the flight did not. The accident was considered my patient's fault, so they brought the guy in. He walked in and was fine, but was wrecked with survivors guilt. I was the highest ranking nurse in the ER that day, and for that reason, the flight incident documentation was assigned to me. I was to perform the mandated blood draw to test the pilot for substances or alcohol. The room was somber. Deaths of people who were close to each other, like brothers, are easily the hardest thing to get through. The pilot's entire squadron, all his bosses, his bosses, bosses were there. I drew his blood. And it's a chain of custody, which means every person who touches the vials has to sign who they handed them off to. For legal purposes. It's all to verify that no one tampered or switched out a vial. I don't know why, but I drew excess blood. Probably because it was my habit to draw a vial or two extra in case a doctor wanted to add tests. So I wouldn't have to stick a patient with a needle twice. When I gathered my trash up, I put them in my pocket. I don't know why I did this. I usually would have just thrown them away, but I had them with me. When the pilot was discharged, his squadron went and got drunk together as they attempted to pull the pilot from an abyss of self blame. I suppose it is important when that's your job, to get past it so you can fly again. And I'm not going to judge anyone for how they managed to do that. It's got to be difficult going back to work with the same people, all of you, knowing you were piloting during an accident that killed other people. So they get a pass to go get blackout drunk. But not an hour after they left, the lab called me. There was a problem. The chain of custody. Blood draws needed to be drawn again. Uncle Raj would lean back, smirking. That's nothing. Priya is going on two years. When the doctor asked her a question at her check up, she just pointed at me to answer. I was working at my assigned station when she approached with this smug expression. She whispered that she dealt with attention seeking students before and that my little act wasn't fooling anyone. I explained again that my prosthetic was real, even offering to show her the attachment point, but she just smiled coldly. Prove it, then she said, loudly enough for nearby students to hear, if it's real, you won't mind me checking. When did you realize that your best friend never liked you? I was always the dumb, ugly, fat friend, and I wouldn't have it any other way. In high school, my best friend not only got all the guys she wanted, but all the girls, too. She was just that pretty blonde hair that didn't move, smelled like Miss Dior, had a nice butt. So when me and Jasmine would go to the library together and guys would only talk to me to try and get to her, I was happy for her. And when her Snapchat was filled with open snaps from hot guys, while mine just had Team Snapchat and my mom, I was happy for her. Not because she didn't rub it in my face. She did. And not because she didn't see herself as better than me, she absolutely did. But because if I had to pick one of us to be the ugly friend, I would choose me every time. Because even though Jasmine could be a bit of a pick me, deep down I knew she had a soft heart, so she needed the world to be kinder to her more than I did. There was just one thing that made me sad. I knew that she would overly rely on her looks to get her through life. And when high school ended, my theory was already proven right because I graduated with a 4.2 GPA. While the only reason Jasmine didn't flunk out Is because the creepy guidance counselor took a liking to her and convinced all the teachers to grade her tests more kindly. I was actually surprised when she spent all summer working, because with the way the world treated her, making her own money was definitely an optional thing. But when I visited her at her job, I realized her version of working was much, much different from mine. She got hired at the trendy boutique downtown where the manager took one look at her and said she'd be perfect for their brand image. Meanwhile, I spent my summer doing data entry at my dad's friend's accounting firm. Mind numbing work that no one would ever call me perfect for. And the more we talked, the more it became obvious to me that we started to see the world very, very differently. It got to the point where I even had to distance myself from her. I started getting all of my updates about her life from her Instagram instead of our usual Facetimes or texts. In just six months, she had gone from 3,000 followers to 200,000, with her comment sections being filled with thirsty amen. She was getting free clothes from expensive brands, invited to brand events, flown to Coachella. But I knew that most of her new friends were probably using her to make themselves look better, so I always made sure to leave wholesome comments under her posts. I sent her gift packages of stuff I knew she loved on her birthday because I always wanted her to know that someone out there me loved her for who she was, not just for her clout. Honestly, I thought I'd never see her again. Until one day when I was 28. I was a well established lawyer, had my own place, and a boyfriend that loved every inch of me unconditionally. And I guess all the milestones reminded me of when I had graduated from high school. Because one day I found myself reaching out to Jasmine again. I mainly just wanted to see if she had changed and if we could be friends. Cause even though I had met some amazing new people, nothing beats someone from your past. We agreed to meet at the usual ice cream place we'd always spend our pocket money on during high school. When I saw her, it took everything in me to hide the shock I felt because her face was pumped with Botox lip filler, not to mention a pound of makeup. After we got through the awkwardly high pitched how are yous? I cut to the chase. Well, kinda. I casually asked if she was working right now. Um, well, you see, I was, but I just smiled because I had an ace up my sleeve. And that ace was a job offer. I told her I was looking for a secretary and I was willing to pay $65,000 a year with benefits. What do I Look like to you an effing charity case? I stared at her blankly and she threw her plastic filled head back and cackled like it was the funniest thing known to mankind. It had been almost 10 years. There's no way she was still like this. I tried to give her the benefit of the doubt and continued, yeah, so you would have to start ASAP. But, um, she interrupted, don't you know I'm an influencer? She then took out her iPhone and showed me her page. I was gaining a new follower once every four months, and all her DMs were from three years ago. That's when I finally realized Jasmine wasn't some misunderstood pretty girl. She was the washed up, textbook definition of I peaked in high school. I was about to walk away, but she stopped me. Hey, don't be sad. With an A that flat, I would be a lawyer too. I tried to make a B line to my car, but she literally ran in front of me and continued, hey, so when do I get to meet your boyfriend?

What's the weirdest past you thought would never catch you? In middle school, I was the meanest girl in our class. Not the popular kind of mean that everyone sees in movies, but the quiet, sneaky kind. I wrote a burn book before Mean Girls made it famous. It was just a pink notebook where I wrote awful things about everyone. Their secrets, their looks, their families. Things I heard in the bathroom or made up when I was bored. My best friend Emma and I would sit at lunch, whispering and laughing while writing in it. We thought we were so cool and smart. No one knew about our book except us. Or so we thought. One day in eighth great, Emma and I had a huge fight over a boy named Tyler. She stopped talking to me, but I kept a burn book. I wrote terrible things about her, too. How her dad lost his job. How she still slept with a nightlight. How her clothes were from Walmart. Stupid kids. Stuff that felt huge back then. When high school started, I made new friends and forgot all about that book. I grew up, realized how awful I'd been, and tried to be better. By college, those mean girl days felt like a different lifetime. I became a teacher, moved to a new city, and built a good life. I never thought about that burn book or those mean days. Ten years later, I was teaching fourth Grade at an elementary school in Chicago. I love my job, my students, and my classroom with its rainbow rug and book corner. I was the teacher I wished I'd had as a kid. Parent teacher conferences came around in October. Over. I sat at my little desk, meeting parents one by one, talking about their kids progress. The door opened for my last meeting of the night, and a woman walked in with a familiar face. My stomach dropped. It was Emma, my old best friend. The one whose secrets I wrote in that burn book. She smiled tightly and sat down. Miss Parker, nice to see you again. I tried to stay calm. Emma, wow. Is Lily your daughter? Lily was one of my quietest students, always reading in the corner. Emma nodded. Yes. Strange coincidence, right? When Lily mentioned her teacher's name, I wasn't sure it was you until I saw the school photo. We talked about Lily's reading skills and math progress. Everything felt normal, but weird. Like we were both pretending. As Emma gathered her papers to leave, I couldn't take it anymore. I'm sorry. I blurted out for everything back then. The things I wrote. I was awful. Emma paused. You know, I found that book after our fight. I took it from your backpack. I read every word. My face burned hot. I'm so sorry. I was terrible person. Yes, you were, she said quietly. I cried for weeks. I waited for her. To yell or say she'd tell the principal about my past. Instead, she pulled out her phone and showed me a picture. It was the burn book. Sitting in a metal trash can, burning. I kept it all these years, not sure what I'd do if I ever saw you again. Then Lily came home, talking about her amazing teacher who makes everyone feel special. Who stands up for the quiet kids, who taught them about bullying. I realized you weren't that girl anymore. She put her phone away. People change. I burned it last night. It's over. The next day, Emma brought cupcakes for the class. As she helped pass them out, she whispered, Lily needs a good teacher. Be that for her. Now. Emma and I get coffee sometimes while Lily reads nearby. We never talk about the Burn Book.

That one time that you had to turn to the dark side. One day, my daughter came back from school and ran into my arms like she was scared. I could feel her shaking, so I took her inside and made some French toast, which was her favorite food. I thought she just had a really bad day and missed being at home, but I couldn't have been more wrong. When she calmed down, she told me, Mommy, something happened today, and I think I'm supposed to tell you about it. An uneasy knot formed itself in my heart when she told me that the school counselor had called her into his office for a special game. He handed my daughter a stuffed unicorn and told her that this new game was very popular with the children, which made my daughter excited and eager to learn. Then the counselor made her point the unicorn between his legs and push on it repeatedly. My daughter told me how he made weird faces at times and then closed his eyes and leaned back. Towards the end, I was so horrified and felt a wave of nausea rush through my body, so I had to go to the bathroom and throw up. I don't know what made me approach the school administration before the police, but that's exactly what I did. And the school administration laughed at me, saying that my daughter was clearly playing a prank. They said they had heard other students make similar jokes about the school counselor and said that parents should teach their kids not to lie. They thought I was a crazy mother who was trying to give merit to my daughter's filthy lie. I had looked straight into my daughter's eyes when she told me the story, so I knew she was telling the truth. But no one wanted to believe me, and I felt like I was in a nightmare.
